Tom,<br>
  The reason I am posting this here is that I am one who does not necessarily use my e-mail address (at least on this site). What good does an e-mail do to give credibility.  There is little credibilty in cyberspace.  When people can hide behind a monitor, they can make up anything.  Beside, if you use an e-mail address, someone can use your e-mail address to send nasty, obscene mail to hundreds or thousands of others.  If you don't believe me, look at the Phil Coleman spectacle on line.  Phil even posted here under assumed names and e-mails.  Look under the Maya Lin thread, there is one poster who posts without all kinds of glaring errors about Maya Lin.  There is a website exposing Phil Coleman as a fraud, a make believe vet and a stealer of e-mail addresses that uses other peoples names and e-mail addresses to send nasty messages to others.  The man is a fraud, and represents some of the dangers of cyberspace.<br>
A name should be good enough here, with an e-mail address optional.  Explain to me why you are so hung up on e-mail addresses.  All that proves, is that someone has a server (on college campuses, many people use one server, e-mail address etc).  E-mail accounts can be faked too as obvious in all the sickos who use cyberspace.  I don't believe that many people come here to find life long friends they would invite to there house, wedding, etc.  This is just cyberspace, take it for what it is.  This site is free and of no cost to anyone, so you have to put up with anyone that comes along (be grateful you are not on the veterans webpage of WWW.enlisted.com)  If you want to talk seriously, I recommend that all of us here REGISTER for one of the veteran chat forums on line, where we can chat with security and credibility.  Many of these forums are free, but require valid information to be part of them.<br>
The reason I say this is that I don't choose to post a e-mail address here for my own reasons (security).  I would share it with others if I felt it necessary.  I was also ignored by you Tom many times because of this.  So, if you feel hung up on an e-mail address then I will have to choose to ignore you as well.  In that case I feel sorry for you, since you are so hung up on a just a website.  For real veteran/war discussion, try a registered chat forum, a college/school discussion/symposium on the war or visit your local VFW, American Legion, Vietnam Veterans of America post, where the people are known.<br><br>
What is said here stays here, why does one need to carry this over to e-mail unless one CHOOSES TO DO SO?  We are not talking about top secret info here, just a open dialog, an open discussion.  If anyone feels that e-mails should be required, then convince PBS to make that a policy here, but I don't see this site sacred enough to have a e-mail address be mandatory.  If it had a higher volume of postings, maybe then so, but not as it is. Sorry!<br><br>
PLEASE NOTE-This message is posted with non hostile intent and is directed in support or against no one.<br>
Nor is it directed in anyway to the debate evolving on this particular thread.<br><br>

